The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Lanka fined for slow over-rate
                                                   CRICKET BRIEFS
                      
	Lanka fined for slow over-rate   
	Calcutta: The Sri Lanka team has been fined for a slow over-rate during their 57-run victory against the West Indies in the semi-final of the World Twenty20 at the Oval on Friday. Match Referee Alan Hurst imposed the fines after the Kumar Sangakkara-led side was ruled to be one over short of their target at the end of the West Indies innings when time allowances were taken into consideration. Sangakkara was fined 10 per cent of his match fee while his players received five per cent finess.  
	Final officials  
	Calcutta: Australian umpires Daryl Harper and Simon Taufel will officiate the final of the mens World Twenty20 between Pakistan and Sri Lanka at Lords on Sunday, the ICC announced on Saturday. Another Australian Steve Davis will be the third umpire while Billy Bowden of New Zealand has been named the fourth umpire of the match, which will be overseen by English Match Referee Chris Broad.  
	President rsquo;s call   
	Karachi: Pakistan President Asif Ali Zardari urged the countrys cricketers on Saturday to give their best in the final of the World Twenty20 against Sri Lanka on Sunday and win the title for the nation. The President called up captain Younis Khan in London and reminded him that the country was passing through a very difficult phase and victory for Pakistan could provide some cheer, media reports said.  
	Meanwhile, PCB chairman Ejaz Butt announced a cash prize of Rs 50 lakh for all-rounder Shahid Afridi, who was adjudged man of the match in the semi-final against South Africa.               
	BCB row   
	Dhaka: The Bangladesh players met with a senior member of the Bangladesh Cricket Board on Saturday to clear the air after unflattering comments were made about their performance at the World Twenty20. The players threatened to boycott a tour of West Indies starting later this month after some senior officials castigated their performance. The outcome has been very positive, said BCB spokesman Rabeed Imam after the meeting.  
	Smith favourite   
	Durban: South Africa cricket captain Graeme Smith and four other players have been nominated for the 2009 Protea Cricketer of the Year award to be presented on June 30, the Cricket South Africa Day, in Johannesburg. The other cricketers who are in the running along with Smith are Ashwell Prince, JP Duminy, AB de Villiers and Dale Steyn. Smith scored a record 1600 Test runs last year and led South Africa to historic away Test series victories over England and Australia.  
	Security issue   
	Wellington: With safety of players topping the agenda of most cricket playing nations, New Zealand Players Association (NZPA) chief Heath Mills has called for pre-tour security inspection and said the NZC is preparing to send a three-member team to Sri Lanka ahead of their upcoming tour. New Zealand is scheduled to visit Sri Lanka in August and September.   A STAFF REPORTER AGENCIES                                                                                                                    
